              <BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><font size="-1">quote:</font><HR>Originally posted by mcdonsco:<BR><BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><font size="-1">quote:</font><HR>Turning off AutoPlay is a good idea anyway, so you might as well kill two birds with one stone here. Then you won't have to hold shift. <HR></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>I always turned it off in the past, but in XP I can't find a way to turn it off and haven't cared enough about it (till now) to look for a way to do it. Anyone?<HR></BLOCKQUOTE>Right click on your drive (you have to do it for each one, so if you have a CDRW and a DVD drive then do it for each if you like).<BR><BR>Once you right click choose Properties, and from there you should see an Autoplay tab.<BR><BR>Now you can select different file types, Music Files, Music CDs, DVDs, etc... (which is nifty)<BR><BR>Then just tell it what you want to do below, so Take No Action would disable autoplay for you in theory.<BR><BR>You can also do it from the registry:<BR><BR><BR>HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\CDRom<BR><BR><BR>If the value for Autorun is 0, then it should be off.<BR><BR>A value of 0xb5 in the following registry key turns off the AutoRun feature for CDs:<BR><BR><BR>HKEY_CURRENT_USER\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Policies\Explorer\NoDriveTypeAutoRun<BR><BR><BR><BR>You must set the hexadecimal value to 91 to enable the AutoRun feature.<BR><BR><BR>(someone may want to check me on that, I think that is the correct data)<BR>--<BR><BR><BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><font size="-1">quote:</font><HR>Originally posted by Ezran:<BR>So now holding down the Shift key is a DMCA violation?<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><BR><BR>I was kind of thinking that too <img src="http://arstechnica.infopop.net/infopop/emoticons/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" width="15" height="15"><!--graemlin::)-->

              

              
              
