              <BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><font size="-1">quote:</font><HR>Originally posted by Richard Berg:<BR>This is getting old.  One does not have (and never had) "Fair Use rights."  FU is an affirmative defense.  If a CD is uncopyable it's a shame*, but it's only "taking away" something you never really had.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE>No one is suggesting that putting copy protection on a CD is illegal.  Granted, the term "fair use <I>rights</I>" is fairly loose language.  They aren't rights, per se, but they are reasonable expectations, and since most of America probably isn't going to know about this before they encounter it and can't encode their CD so they can listen to it on their iPod (or any other action that could fall under fair use), I think it's a valid complaint.<BR><BR>I think it's fair to say that part of the perceived value of a CD is the ability to make a copy for personal use.  When the record labels obfuscate the process making it so that joe consumer can't do this, I think they should be held legally accountable to make it obvious that they have changed their product, and how.  No marketing speak, just straight up making it clear what this "technology" will not allow the buyer to do with the CD.

              

              
              
            </div>
